But in-in terms of, in terms of big things
to figure out how to deal with, we've been

00:34:27.359 --> 00:34:31.520
doing a lot with parallel programming; two
different levels where we're trying to deal

00:34:31.520 --> 00:34:39.149
with this. One is, one is the big distributed
system, the Cloud, where we've worked some

00:34:39.149 --> 00:34:41.950
with Google, Reston on this.

00:34:41.950 --> 00:34:48.310
The other is sort of the fine grain OpenMP
NVIDIA CUDA type approach. And at that point

00:34:48.310 --> 00:34:52.740
we also use, there's a system at the University
of Maryland called XMT that tries to get at

00:34:52.740 --> 00:34:57.440
sort of algorithms. What does the algorithm
look like at a, at very fine level? Not what's

00:34:57.440 --> 00:34:58.940
this big problem and I'll just break it up
into pieces and send it out on-on the Cloud

00:34:58.940 --> 00:35:06.240
or I wanna run ten thousand different-different
designs to figure out what's-what's the best

00:35:06.240 --> 00:35:13.480
and I send each one out on a Cloud. Not that.
But just to get one of these simulations or

00:35:13.480 --> 00:35:16.440
whatever to run, how do I get this loop to
go faster?

00:35:16.440 --> 00:35:19.470
And so those are very different problems.

00:35:19.470 --> 00:35:25.359
And then the in-in-in terms of data, the people,
not the people I'm working with directly,

00:35:25.359 --> 00:35:30.540
but some of people at George Mason are involved
in this LSST project that's it-it's gonna

00:35:30.540 --> 00:35:38.231
create a huge amount of data. I-I don't know
how much in high school that will, that will

00:35:38.231 --> 00:35:40.300
show up.

00:35:40.300 --> 00:35:44.720
In the elective courses in the lab we try
to get problems to be of a sufficient size

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:48.951
that if your algorithms aren't good you can
actually tell, but I don't know it could,

00:35:48.951 --> 00:35:50.400
it could just be too big.

00:35:50.400 --> 00:36:00.431
Let me give two possibilities for-for, as
far as where else, where-where does computing

00:36:00.431 --> 00:36:05.940
go in high school if CS is doing poorly itself?
I'll give you two examples at-at TJ. We have

00:36:05.940 --> 00:36:10.900
a math class Numerical Analysis for the past
five years. It's actually run I don't know

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:15.760
maybe four times. It doesn't-doesn't always
run every year. But it uses MATLAB and depending

00:36:15.760 --> 00:36:19.960
on the instructor that it's either like MATLAB
where you write a lot of code or MATLAB where

00:36:19.960 --> 00:36:23.410
you don't write as much code. You kinda go
either way.

00:36:23.410 --> 00:36:28.140
And we've had a computational Physics course
for-for many years which is taught by a physics

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:33.710
teacher who-who writes code. And that most
recently is-is-is been in Mathematica. Where

00:36:33.710 --> 00:36:40.430
again, depending on, it sort of depends on
the instructor these are systems where maybe

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:44.900
you really write a lot of code and maybe not,
depending on how it's done.

00:36:44.900 --> 00:36:49.290
Another possibility, and again these are all
enrollment numbers, rough enrollment numbers.

00:36:49.290 --> 00:36:54.380
So this is not a lot of students in-in-in
terms of what's happening now.

00:36:54.380 --> 00:37:00.310
In terms of-of potential, we have lots of
students taking math and science courses and

00:37:00.310 --> 00:37:04.359
there are places where obviously you can imagine
in math and science in high school with good-good

00:37:04.359 --> 00:37:10.500
students, where you can imagine doing-doing
something that-that-that's in the direction

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:11.730
of computing.

00:37:11.730 --> 00:37:17.670
This is way easier said than done because
you have huge sort of teacher recruitment

00:37:17.670 --> 00:37:25.881
training issues. I mean it's hard enough to
keep teachers teaching CS to then say to teachers

00:37:25.881 --> 00:37:31.180
teaching chemistry that you've gotta have
now your all-all-all your students in your

00:37:31.180 --> 00:37:32.180
class write code.

00:37:32.180 --> 00:37:36.730
I'll-I'll believe it when I see it, but it's
one-one possibility.

00:37:36.730 --> 00:37:42.090
But what that doesn't answer, these are a
few things we've been working on. We're always,

00:37:42.090 --> 00:37:46.830
computer systems are always trying to push
the envelope constantly. We try not to get

00:37:46.830 --> 00:37:47.930
too comfortable ever.

00:37:47.930 --> 00:37:53.970
So a couple of things we've working on the
last-last couple of years: biology sort of

00:37:53.970 --> 00:37:59.900
gene sequence type matching programs where
you actually take from public databases and

00:37:59.900 --> 00:38:02.210
then you build these little tree of life drawings.

00:38:02.210 --> 00:38:11.390
We've been doing things with CUDA now for-for
two or three years as we're programming on

00:38:11.390 --> 00:38:13.850
the, on the, on the, directly on the NVIDIA
graphics card.

00:38:13.850 --> 00:38:15.510
You know we get better at it.

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:20.830
The picture of Darwin and the Mona Lisa -- that's
approximating an image with transparent polygons,

00:38:20.830 --> 00:38:25.820
so it's like a genetic algorithm type problem.
I mean this is the kind of thing that when

00:38:25.820 --> 00:38:28.500
you're 16, you can actually write code and
do this and it's like, "WOW! This is really

00:38:28.500 --> 00:38:30.360
cool!"

00:38:30.360 --> 00:38:33.859
So that gets a lot, a lot of, a lot of buy
in.

00:38:33.859 --> 00:38:38.460
The water wheel is supposed to be like a design
problem. We've-we've never really known exactly

00:38:38.460 --> 00:38:48.089
how to tie into engineering courses. We've,
it's a lot easier to tie into physics or statistics.

00:38:48.089 --> 00:38:54.640
But I think there might be something here
because there's obviously a lot of renewed

00:38:54.640 --> 00:38:58.410
interest in-in energy and-and in efficiency.

00:38:58.410 --> 00:39:03.849
And my personal favorite is this asteroids
program 'cause beginning students particularly

00:39:03.849 --> 00:39:07.930
in the summer, you get students who are like
way ahead of the-the regular pace and they

00:39:07.930 --> 00:39:12.230
wanna know what to do. My-my stock answer
is to have 'em try to do asteroids because

00:39:12.230 --> 00:39:16.720
with one, I feel like I can teach almost half
a semester just off of this one little, this

00:39:16.720 --> 00:39:23.390
one little game in terms of control and the,
and it's sort of right at the right point

00:39:23.390 --> 00:39:28.251
of-of-of-of-of trig and-and what they know
about velocity and acceleration and-and how

00:39:28.251 --> 00:39:34.099
they manage lists. And we try to get the asteroid
to break apart. How they manage objects.

00:39:34.099 --> 00:39:40.230
I don't know who would do that if not a computer
science course. That's not, I still think

00:39:40.230 --> 00:39:48.849
any-anything in that arena would happen. So.

00:39:48.849 --> 00:39:53.350
And I've tried to do a little bit of a fly
by here so if there's, af-afterwards when

00:39:53.350 --> 00:39:58.250
we do the questions, [ ] questions, I could
